Humans are the world's most institutionally dominant people — not strongest, most magical, or most perceptive, but most relentless as builders. They construct roads, cities, legal systems, archives, and hierarchies with an urgency other races find simultaneously admirable and alarming. The world's major institutions — Keeper road networks, the Great Pyramid, the Salt Ledger Kingdoms, oasis corridor water law, Midgaard's civic governance, Kowloon's delta trade empire — are human constructions. So are the world's most catastrophic institutional failures: the Spirebound Conclave's condemned-labor programs, the sealed warrants, the Black Ledger, and the Ashfall Era's compounded disasters. Humans occupy a causal position rather than a moral one: most of what shapes this world, for good and ill, traces back to human decisions inside human institutions. Stat profile: STR/INT/WIS/DEX/CON all 19 — balanced rather than exceptional. No elemental affinities, resistances, weaknesses, or racial skills. Their defining advantage is adaptation: they can become whatever their institutions make them. Black Sun Shard drove early civilization toward record-keeping as survival. Keeper Era built road networks and cisterns through measurement-as-governance. Solar Court constructed the Great Pyramid to contain the Shard. Salt Ledger Kingdoms followed. Ashfall Era produced the Spirebound Conclave's atrocities, sealed warrants, and the Black Ledger. Contemporary: Midgaard's Continuity vs Reckoning faction split over acknowledging the sealed-warrant crimes; Kowloon's Jade Magistracy maintains the Black Ledger sealed.

