Kowloon's institutional framework is the Neon Covenant — the five-house governance structure whose authority traces through both legitimate commerce and the Black Ledger's sealed secrets. Humans in Kowloon are classified by house affiliation, color-jurisdiction standing, and Jade Magistracy registration. The Courier Lantern Office manages transit documentation; the Black Ledger remains sealed in an undercity cistern. The five houses whose authority governs Kowloon's civic structure each maintain separate registry systems, and color jurisdiction determines which house's courts adjudicate disputes. The Jade Magistracy's refusal to open the Black Ledger is simultaneously a legal decision, a political choice, and a daily demonstration that human institutions will choose comfortable suppression over difficult truth indefinitely. Deltari communities built the hydraulic infrastructure that keeps Kowloon viable and are excluded from formal governance. The Jade Magistracy considers Deltari parallel flow records a civic nuisance rather than authoritative documentation. Neon Covenant charter provides for crisis intervention protocols that can be invoked by any two houses jointly — this is the mechanism by which the Magistracy has historically contained Reckoning-equivalent movements before they accumulated institutional traction. Human identity in Kowloon is commercially indexed: guild standing, house patronage, and trade route access determine civic weight.

