Ashborn in Midgaard live inside the administrative consequence of human institutional bad faith. The Ash-and-Iron Decades' misclassification — registering Ashborn as "ashfall survivors" without separate civic identity to deny them inheritance and property standing during reconstruction — is not historical abstraction for Ashborn residents. It is the specific registry entry that affects their reclassification petitions today. Midgaard's foundry and construction districts are functionally Ashborn-majority neighborhoods whose residents are registered under classifications that deny their distinct identity. The Hammers Guild recognizes Ashborn forge-workers; the Lantern Registry classifies them under contested categories. Reckoning faction scholars cite Ashborn misclassification as the clearest evidence that the sealed warrants represent a pattern of institutional bad faith rather than isolated administrative error. Continuity faction archivists maintain that reclassification petitions are the appropriate mechanism and decline to treat the original classification as a founding institutional crime. Ashborn in Midgaard are essential to the city's metalwork economy and categorically excluded from the civic standing that would allow them to formally contest their own classification. The forge is where they work; the registry is where the institutional wound remains open.

