Deltari in Kowloon experience human institutional governance as extraction with documentation suppression. The hydraulic infrastructure they built keeps the city viable; the Jade Magistracy excludes them from formal civic power while depending on their practical expertise. The Black Ledger — sealed census of individuals transferred to the Conclave, including Deltari names — is the most acute expression of this dynamic: the city that needed Deltari knowledge also transferred Deltari people to Conclave experimentation and then sealed the record. Deltari flow records of Kowloon's actual history — maintained in parallel to official Jade Magistracy records, documenting the hydraulic decisions, population movements, and institutional choices that the official record elides — constitute the most effective leverage Deltari communities hold. The Magistracy cannot suppress records it does not hold. Human governance of Kowloon from a Deltari perspective is a system that is entirely dependent on Deltari expertise and constitutionally unable to acknowledge that dependency without undermining the political authority that the five houses derive from claiming credit for what the Deltari built. Reed Law's principle — the record is the agreement, and a hidden record is a violated agreement — makes the Black Ledger's continued sealing the central civic wrong from a Deltari standpoint.

